			<h4><a id="comment_link_64251072" name="comment_link_64251072" href="//tech.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23231052&amp;cid=64251072" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64251072)" >Re:</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64251072" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64251072); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>3</a>, Insightful)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~hyperar">hyperar</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~hyperar">( 3992287 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64251072"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64251072">Charging standard is the least of the problems, EVs are:
-Expensive to buy and to maintain (battery replacement in the tens of thousands).
-Unreliable.
-Insurance is more expensive.
-Charging takes hours and charging stations are no way near what car/diesel vehicles have.
-Weather can shorten significally the range and can impact charging availability.

The first 3 items already rules out 99% of the potential buyers, at this point, they're nothing more than a novelty and a stupid product.</div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64251072">

